## Phase 3: Visual parity check against Codex.app

### Overview

Side-by-side visual comparison with the installed Codex.app. Not automated — the goal is catching ad-hoc spacing/weight regressions, not pixel-perfect diff.

### Preparation

Codex shows its onboarding login screen only when signed out. If you're already signed into Codex, reset its state:

```bash
# macOS — reset Codex's signed-in state so the onboarding page renders
rm -rf ~/Library/Application\ Support/Codex/Cookies*
rm -rf ~/Library/Application\ Support/Codex/Partitions
# Or: delete ~/Library/Application\ Support/Codex entirely for a full reset (destructive)
```

> **Note**: the `rm -rf` above targets Codex's own userData, not Lightfast's. If you're not comfortable clearing Codex state, skip this step and work from memory / screenshots of Codex's onboarding page instead.

### Changes Required

None — this phase is verification only.

### Success Criteria

#### Manual Verification (side-by-side)

Run both apps simultaneously:

```bash
# Terminal 1
open -a Codex

# Terminal 2 (from repo root)
pnpm dev:desktop
```

Compare visually:

- [ ] **Logo size**: both ~48px tall, similar visual weight
- [ ] **Logo-to-title gap**: both show ~16px vertical rhythm
- [ ] **Title-to-subtitle gap**: both show ~4px (tight coupling)
- [ ] **Subtitle-to-actions gap**: both show ~32px (visual break before CTA)
- [ ] **Button column width**: both cap at ~200px; buttons stretch the full width
- [ ] **Button padding**: both have ~10px vertical inner padding (CTA feels tappable, not dense)
- [ ] **Button-to-button gap**: both show ~12px between primary and secondary
- [ ] **Typography hierarchy**: title is visibly heavier / larger than subtitle; both centered
- [ ] **Centering**: both lay out on the vertical center of the window, not top-anchored

Acceptable divergences:

- Our pill buttons vs Codex's rounded-md buttons (intentional, see 2.1 note)
- Our static logo vs Codex's animated "hello" logo (intentional, deferred)
- Our two-button column vs Codex's (ChatGPT + API key) — different products, same layout shape

Unacceptable divergences — if seen, iterate on CSS:

- Overlay does not cover sidebar
- Titlebar drag region broken (cannot drag window)
- Theme swap produces unreadable contrast
- Buttons misaligned or column exceeds 200px

---

## Phase 4: Interaction smoke tests

### Overview

Verify the signed-out shell interacts correctly with Phase 4 (`auth-flow.ts`) and the existing `openExternal` channel. These tests are manual — the renderer has no test runner configured.

### Changes Required

None.

### Success Criteria

#### Manual Verification — golden path

1. [ ] Desktop launched signed-out → overlay visible
2. [ ] Click **Sign in with Lightfast** → Electron BrowserWindow opens at `http://localhost:3024/desktop/auth?state=…` (NOT the system browser)
3. [ ] Complete Clerk sign-in inside the BrowserWindow → BrowserWindow closes automatically → overlay unmounts → signed-in UI (`<AccountCard />` + Sign out button) renders
4. [ ] Relaunch Electron — token persists from keychain → signed-in UI renders immediately, overlay is never visible
5. [ ] Click **Sign out** in signed-in UI → overlay re-renders immediately

#### Manual Verification — learn-more path

6. [ ] From signed-out overlay, click **Learn more** → `https://lightfast.ai` opens in the default system browser (Safari/Chrome), NOT inside Electron
7. [ ] Desktop window stays on the signed-out overlay (no navigation)

#### Manual Verification — negative paths

8. [ ] Click **Sign in**, then close the BrowserWindow before completing Clerk sign-in → `beginSignIn()` resolves to `null` → overlay stays exactly as-is, primary button re-clickable
9. [ ] Click **Sign in**, let `SIGNIN_TIMEOUT_MS` elapse (5 minutes) → overlay stays as-is, no error, no stuck state (Phase 4 already handles this; we confirm the overlay observes no side-effects)
10. [ ] Corrupt `~/Library/Application Support/Lightfast/auth.bin` with `printf "garbage" > ...`, relaunch → overlay renders (token load fails cleanly → treated as signed-out, no crash)
11. [ ] Toggle `<html>` class between `electron-dark` and `electron-light` via devtools → overlay re-themes instantly, no FOUC

#### Regression checks

12. [ ] Existing settings route (`#/settings`) still works after sign-in (i.e., overlay doesn't leak above non-home routes once signed in)
13. [ ] Secondary window (Cmd+Shift+N or menu) still opens and is independent of overlay
14. [ ] HUD window still opens and is independent

---

## Testing Strategy

### Unit Tests

None. `SignedOutShell` is a pure presentation component with two callback props — trivial enough that an integration smoke test (Phase 4 above) is sufficient. If `apps/desktop` later gains a test runner (currently has none per `package.json`), consider adding:

- Snapshot test that `SignedOutShell` renders heading/subtitle/button labels
- Click handlers fire the passed callbacks

### Integration Tests

None. The CDP harness added in `apps/desktop/src/main/bootstrap.ts` (per desktop-clerk-trpc-wiring.md Improvement Log) could later drive the overlay through a Playwright session. Not required for first ship.

### Manual Testing Steps

See Phase 3 (visual parity) and Phase 4 (interaction smoke tests).

## Performance Considerations

- Overlay mounts/unmounts are React re-renders of <10 nodes — trivial cost.
- Inlined SVG path data adds ~8 KB to the renderer bundle (`Icons.logoShort`). If a second inlined SVG appears, consider extracting to a shared `desktop-icons.tsx`.
- No network fetches, no animations, no timers — zero runtime cost after mount.

## Migration Notes

- **No data migration.** This replaces inline JSX with a component reference.
- **Rollback**: revert `app-shell.tsx` to the 10-line inline JSX; remove `signed-out-shell.tsx` and the `.auth-gate__*` CSS block. No persistent state touched.

